04747nam a22007215i 9780226705033DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019053421  a9780226705033  a(DE-B1597)566826  a(OCoLC)1202466634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aN75b.R67 2020 4aN75b.R67 2021 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a701.182231 aRoss, Stephanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTwo Thumbs Up :bHow Critics Aid Appreciation /cStephanie Ross. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Taste and Preference -- t2. Aesthetic Qualities -- t3. Hume on the Standard of Taste -- t4. Identifying Critics -- t5. When Critics Disagree -- t6. Comparing and Sharing Taste -- t7. Some Applications -- tAppendix: A Checklist for Appreciation -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFar from an elite practice reserved for the highly educated, criticism is all around us. We turn to the Yelp reviewers to decide what restaurants are best, to Rotten Tomatoes to guide our movie choices, and to a host of voices on social media for critiques of political candidates, beach resorts, and everything in between. Yet even amid this ever-expanding sea of opinions, professional critics still hold considerable power in guiding how we make aesthetic judgements. Philosophers and lovers of art continue to grapple with questions that have fascinated them for centuries: How should we engage with works of art? What might enhance such encounters? Should some people’s views be privileged? Who should count as a critic? And do critics actually help us appreciate art? In Two Thumbs Up, philosopher Stephanie Ross tackles these questions, revealing the ways that critics influence our decisions, and why that’s a good thing. Starting from David Hume’s conception of ideal critics, Ross refines his position and makes the case that review-based journalistic or consumer reporting criticism proves the best model for helping us find and appreciate quality. She addresses and critiques several other positions and, in the process, she demonstrates how aesthetic and philosophical concerns permeate our lives, choices, and culture. Ultimately, whether we’re searching for the right wine or the best concert, Ross encourages us all to find and follow critics whose taste we share.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAesthetics. 0aArt appreciation. 0aArt criticism. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aArt-Philosophy. 0aHume, David,-1711-1776. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aHume.  aaesthetics.  aappreciation.  acritics.  adisagreement.  ataste.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110704648oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226705033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226705033/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070482-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZ